    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-11-03T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-11-03T03:00:00-05:00" n="353"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d353">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 P.W./604: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Saigon</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Browne</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Saigon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-11-03T15:00:00+07:00"
                            >November 3, 1941—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 6—9:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>123. Department’s telegram of October 31, 7 [<hi rend="italic">8</hi>] p.m.<note
                        n="22" xml:id="d353fn1">Not printed.</note> regarding Japanese troops and
                    aircraft in southern Indochina. While increasing secrecy surrounds Japanese
                    troop movements, the consensus of opinion among qualified observers is that not
                    more than 32,000 are now stationed in southern Indochina, distributed roughly as
                    follows: Cambodia 10,000, Saigon 8,000, Cochin-China apart from Saigon 12,000,
                    coastal areas of Nhatrang and Camranh 2,000. The same observers place the number
                    of Japanese troops in Tongking at 18,000, including most recent arrivals, making
                    a total of 50,000 for Indochina. It is believed that this figure should be
                    considered a maximum.</p>
                <p>With regard to aircraft, little accurate information can be obtained but reliable
                    sources estimate a maximum of 150 of which the large majority consists of
                    bombers. They are now concentrated mainly at Saigon.</p>
                <p>Sent to Cavite for repetition to the Department, Chungking, Peiping, Hong Kong,
                    Shanghai. Shanghai please repeat to Tokyo. Repeated to Bangkok.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Browne</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
